WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:15.636
A girl I've never met before
我之前从没遇见过的一个女孩

2
00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:18.940
changed my life and the life of thousands of other people.
改变了我的生活，也改变了千千万万人的生活

3
00:00:19.580 --> 00:00:21.980
I'm the CEO of DoSomething.org.
我是“有所作为”(DoSomething.org)这个网站的首席执行官

4
00:00:22.380 --> 00:00:26.796
It's one of the largest organizations in the world for young people.
它是世界上为年轻人所创建的最大的网站之一

5
00:00:26.820 --> 00:00:29.716
In fact it's bigger than the Boy Scouts in the United States.
说实话，它的规模比美国的“童子军”还大

6
00:00:29.740 --> 00:00:31.276
And we're not homophobic.
而且我们不是反对同性恋的网站

7
00:00:31.300 --> 00:00:33.460
(Laughter)
（笑声）

8
00:00:33.900 --> 00:00:37.436
And it's true -- the way we communicate with young people is by text,
对，我们是通过短信跟年轻人交流

9
00:00:37.460 --> 00:00:39.820
because that's how young people communicate.
因为这是现在年轻人的交流方式

10
00:00:40.300 --> 00:00:43.875
So we'll run over 200 campaigns this year,
因此，今年我们会组织超过200个活动

11
00:00:43.900 --> 00:00:47.596
things like collecting peanut butter for food pantries,
比如给食物站收集花生酱

12
00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:52.460
or making Valentine's Day cards for senior citizens who are homebound.
或者给返乡老人制作情人节卡片

13
00:00:52.820 --> 00:00:54.276
And we'll text them.
然后我们会给他们发短信

14
00:00:54.300 --> 00:00:57.236
And we'll have a 97 percent open rate.
而这些短信有97%的阅读率

15
00:00:57.260 --> 00:00:59.956
It'll over-index Hispanic and urban.
这在西班牙裔和城市中都是超过平均水平的

16
00:00:59.980 --> 00:01:03.956
We collected 200,000 jars of peanut butter
我们收集了超过20万罐花生酱

17
00:01:03.980 --> 00:01:08.356
and over 365,000 Valentine's Day cards.
制作了超过36.5万张情人节卡片

18
00:01:08.380 --> 00:01:10.156
This is big scale. OK --
这规模挺大的

19
00:01:10.180 --> 00:01:12.860
(Applause)
（喝彩）

20
00:01:13.460 --> 00:01:15.100
But there's one weird side effect.
但这些活动引发了一个很奇怪的副作用

21
00:01:15.660 --> 00:01:18.756
Every time we send out a text message,
每当我们发出一条短信之后

22
00:01:18.780 --> 00:01:23.076
we get back a few dozen text messages having nothing to do with peanut butter
我们会收到很多回信

23
00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:25.876
or hunger or senior citizens --
这些回信跟花生酱、饥荒、或者老年人没有一点关系

24
00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:29.396
but text messages about being bullied,
而是关于被霸凌

25
00:01:29.420 --> 00:01:32.220
text messages about being addicted to pot.
或者是关于大麻上瘾

26
00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:36.980
And the worst message we ever got said exactly this:
并且我们确实得说 我们收到过最糟糕的短信是这个：

27
00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:40.020
"He won't stop raping me.
“他会一直强奸我，“

28
00:01:40.540 --> 00:01:42.060
It's my dad.
“他是我爸爸。”

29
00:01:42.860 --> 00:01:46.660
He told me not to tell anyone. Are you there?"
他让我不要告诉任何人。 有人在吗？

30
00:01:50.058 --> 00:01:51.916
We couldn't believe this was happening.
我们无法相信这是真实发生过的事情

31
00:01:51.940 --> 00:01:55.596
We couldn't believe that something so horrific could happen to a human being,
我们简直无法相信这么可怕的事情 会发生在一个真实的人身上

32
00:01:55.620 --> 00:01:59.260
and that she would share it with us -- something so intimate, so personal.
而她却把这么私密的事情告诉我们

33
00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:02.556
And we realized we had to stop triaging this
因此我们意识到,我们必须要给这些短信分类

34
00:02:02.580 --> 00:02:06.580
and we had to build a crisis text line for these people in pain.
我们应该建立给这些正在遭受痛苦的人 建立一个危机短信专线

35
00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:09.900
So we launched Crisis Text Line,
为此我们很隐秘地在芝加哥和埃尔帕索 建立了“危机短信专线”，

36
00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:16.276
very quietly, in Chicago and El Paso -- just a few thousand people in each market.
每条线路只有几千人

37
00:02:16.300 --> 00:02:21.036
And in four months, we were in all 295 area codes in America.
并且四个月内我们在美国295个区域号码内都建立了这个专线。

38
00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:22.680
Just to put that into perspective,
这个扩展的规模,对比地说

39
00:02:22.703 --> 00:02:26.316
that's zero marketing and faster growth than when Facebook first launched.
我们从零开始创建和扩展这个领域， 比脸书刚建立时还要发展得更快

40
00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:30.876
(Applause)
（喝彩）

41
00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:33.276
Text is unbelievably private.
短信是及其隐秘的一种方式

42
00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:34.996
No one hears you talking.
因为没人能听到你在说什么

43
00:02:35.020 --> 00:02:37.116
So we spike everyday at lunch time --
所以每次在午饭时间我们的短信数量就会飙升

44
00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:38.836
kids are sitting at the lunch table
当孩子们坐在午餐桌旁边的时候

45
00:02:38.860 --> 00:02:42.036
and you think that she's texting the cute boy across the hall,
你觉得她正在给旅馆大堂的某个男孩子发短信

46
00:02:42.060 --> 00:02:44.700
but she's actually texting us about her bulimia.
但她其实是在给我们讲述她的贪食症

47
00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:48.876
And we don't get the word "like" or "um" or hyperventilating or crying.
我们不会听到类似“好像”，“ 呃” ，急喘声或者哭声

48
00:02:48.900 --> 00:02:50.660
We just get facts.
我们只会看到事实

49
00:02:52.020 --> 00:02:55.636
We get things like, "I want to die.
我们会收到类似的消息：“ 我想自杀。”

50
00:02:55.660 --> 00:02:58.580
I have a bottle of pills on the desk in front of me."
“在我面前的书桌前有一瓶药。“

51
00:02:59.020 --> 00:03:01.116
And so the crisis counselor says,
那么我们的危机顾问就会说：

52
00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:04.140
"How about you put those pills in the drawer while we text?"
“ 在我们还在发短信的时候把你的药片放进抽屉里怎么样？“

53
00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:07.956
And they go back and forth for a while.
他们会僵持一会儿

54
00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:10.980
And the crisis counselor gets the girl to give her her address,
然后我们的危机顾问会向这个女孩要她的地址

55
00:03:11.020 --> 00:03:13.716
because if you're texting a text line, you want help.
因为如果你给短信热线发消息，这证明你其实想要获得帮助

56
00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:14.916
So she gets the address
因此她给了地址

57
00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:17.116
and the counselor triggers an active rescue
我们的危机顾问在他们发短信的期间

58
00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:19.140
while they're texting back and forth.
采取措施营救这个女孩

59
00:03:19.820 --> 00:03:23.036
And then it goes quiet --
然后一切都变安静了

60
00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:27.700
23 minutes with no response from this girl.
23分钟里我们都没收到这个女孩的回信

61
00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:31.436
And the next message that comes in says --
后来收到一条消息说：

62
00:03:31.460 --> 00:03:33.076
it's the mom --
“我是她妈妈，”

63
00:03:33.100 --> 00:03:36.676
"I had no idea, and I was in the house,
“我不知道怎么办，我当时在屋里”

64
00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:39.180
we're in an ambulance on our way to the hospital."
“我们现在坐着救护车在去医院的路上”

65
00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:41.900
As a mom that one just --
作为一个母亲，我...“

66
00:03:44.580 --> 00:03:46.700
The next message comes a month later.
一个月后我们收到了她们发来的另一条短信

67
00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:48.796
"I just got out of the hospital.
“我刚从医院出来。”

68
00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:52.340
I was diagnosed as bipolar, and I think I'm going to be OK."
“我被确诊为人格分裂，我觉我会没事儿的。”

69
00:03:53.260 --> 00:03:55.956
(Applause)
（喝彩）

70
00:03:55.980 --> 00:04:00.636
I would love to tell you that that's an unusual exchange,
我很高兴告诉你们这是一个不同寻常的改变，

71
00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:05.196
but we're doing on average 2.41 active rescues a day.
但是我们平均每天会采取2.41个营救措施

72
00:04:05.220 --> 00:04:10.180
Thirty percent of our text messages are about suicide and depression -- huge.
我们收到30%的短信都是关于自杀或者绝望

73
00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:12.756
The beautiful thing about Crisis Text Line
危机短信热线最美好的一面就是

74
00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:16.356
is that these are strangers counseling other strangers
陌生人给另一个陌生人

75
00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:19.036
on the most intimate issues,
在非常隐秘的问题上施以援手

76
00:04:19.060 --> 00:04:21.436
and getting them from hot moments to cold moments.
将他们从痛苦难熬的时刻拯救出来

77
00:04:21.460 --> 00:04:23.756
It's exciting, and I will tell you
我必须的说，这真的很振奋人心

78
00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:28.036
that we have done a total of more than 6.5 million text messages
因为我们在过去不超过两年的时间里

79
00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:29.356
in less than two years.
传输了超过650万条短信

80
00:04:29.380 --> 00:04:34.356
(Applause)
（喝彩）

81
00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:37.596
But the thing that really gets me hot and sweaty about this,
但最令我热血澎湃

82
00:04:37.620 --> 00:04:40.476
the thing that really gets me psyched is the data:
最令我激动不已的事情是这个数据：

83
00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:42.836
6.5 million messages --
这650万条短信

84
00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:48.500
that's the volume, velocity and variety to provide a really juicy corpus.
这数量、速度和多样性给我们提供了丰富的语料库

85
00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:50.676
We can do things like predictive work.
这使得我们能够提前预警

86
00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:55.236
We can do all kinds of conclusions and learnings from that data set.
我们能够从这些数据中得到各种结论

87
00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:58.476
So we can be better, and the world can be better.
因此，我们能做得更好，这个世界也会变得更好

88
00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:00.916
So how do we use the data to make us better?
所以我们是如何通过这些数据做得更好的呢？

89
00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:04.276
Alright, chances are someone here, someone watching this
好了，在场的人，正在看这个视频的人

90
00:05:04.300 --> 00:05:07.876
has seen a therapist or a shrink at some point in time in your life --
过去曾看过临床医学家或者精神病医师的人

91
00:05:07.900 --> 00:05:09.567
you do not have to raise your hand.
你们不用举手示意了

92
00:05:09.591 --> 00:05:11.196
(Laughter)
（笑声）

93
00:05:11.220 --> 00:05:13.476
How do you know that person's any good?
你们怎么知道他们能带来任何改变？

94
00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:15.756
Oh, they have a degree from Harvard on the wall?
哦，对了，他们有装裱好挂在墙的哈佛毕业证书

95
00:05:15.780 --> 00:05:18.447
Are you sure he didn't graduate in the bottom 10 percent?
但你能确定他们不是后10%的毕业生？

96
00:05:18.471 --> 00:05:19.876
(Laughter)
（笑声）

97
00:05:19.900 --> 00:05:22.116
When my husband and I saw a marriage counselor,
以前我和我丈夫看到过一个已婚的咨询师

98
00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:24.093
I thought she was a genius when she said,
我当时觉得她很机智当她说：

99
00:05:24.117 --> 00:05:27.556
"I'll see you guys in two weeks -- but I need to see you next week, sir."
“我会在接下来的两周跟你们见面，但是我得下周跟你先见一面，先生。”

100
00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:30.236
(Laughter)
（笑声）

101
00:05:30.260 --> 00:05:33.180
We have the data to know what makes a great counselor.
我们有庞大的数据帮助咨询师做好自己的工作

102
00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:38.476
We know that if you text the words "numbs" and "sleeve,"
我们知道如果你发的消息很机械化很麻木

103
00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:41.636
there's a 99 percent match for cutting.
那你有99%的概率可能是被裁员了

104
00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:46.476
We know that if you text in the words "mg" and "rubber band,"
我们明白如果你发的消息像“毫克” 或者“橡皮筋”

105
00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:49.780
there's a 99 percent match for substance abuse.
那你有99%的概率是滥用药物的人

106
00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:55.916
And we know that if you text in "sex," "oral" and "Mormon,"
我也知道如果你的消息里包括 “性”， “口头的” 和“摩门教”，

107
00:05:55.940 --> 00:05:57.700
you're questioning if you're gay.
你可能正在质疑自己是不是同性恋

108
00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:02.476
Now that's interesting information that a counselor could figure out
虽然我们的咨询师也能分析出来这些有用的信息,

109
00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:06.636
but that algorithm in our hands means that an automatic pop-up says,
但是我们现有的算法能够启动识别并提示咨询师

110
00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:11.036
"99 percent match for cutting -- try asking one of these questions"
"(这条短信) 99％ 都和裁员有关，

111
00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:12.396
to prompt the counselor.
建议问这几个裁员相关的问题.”

112
00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:15.196
Or "99 percent match for substance abuse,
或者“99％都和滥用药物有关，”

113
00:06:15.220 --> 00:06:18.860
here are three drug clinics near the texter."
在这个发信息的人附近有三个药物门诊。”

114
00:06:19.380 --> 00:06:21.060
It makes us more accurate.
这样是我们的能够更加精确。

115
00:06:22.060 --> 00:06:24.796
On the day that Robin Williams committed suicide,
在威廉姆.罗宾自杀身亡的那天

116
00:06:24.820 --> 00:06:27.076
people flooded hotlines all over this country.
整个国家的人将电话热线都淹没了

117
00:06:27.100 --> 00:06:31.356
It was sad to see an icon, a funnyman, commit suicide,
我们很不幸看到一代偶像，一个有趣的男人自杀了

118
00:06:31.380 --> 00:06:35.076
and there were three hour wait times on every phone hotline in the country.
这个国家的每个电话热线都得等待三小时

119
00:06:35.100 --> 00:06:37.436
We had a spike in volume also.
我们的短信数量也急剧飚升

120
00:06:37.460 --> 00:06:38.716
The difference was
但不同的是

121
00:06:38.740 --> 00:06:42.676
if you text us, "I want to die," or "I want to kill myself,"
如果你给我们发消息说：“我想去死，” 或者“我想自杀。”

122
00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:46.156
the algorithm reads that, you're code orange,
我们的计算机运算系统读过之后，你的消息会被标注橙色警报

123
00:06:46.180 --> 00:06:48.356
and you become number one in the queue.
然后你会被排到等候队列的第一个

124
00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:51.476
So we can handle severity, not chronological.
因此我们会按严重程度处理，而不是按时间顺序

125
00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:56.636
(Applause)
（掌声）

126
00:06:56.660 --> 00:06:58.996
This data is also making the world better
我们的数据也使得这个世界变得更好

127
00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:04.516
because I'm sitting on the world's first map of real-time crises.
因为我正坐在世界上第一张实时危机的地图前时刻观测着

128
00:07:04.540 --> 00:07:05.756
Think about it:
想想吧：

129
00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:10.156
those 6.5 million messages, auto-tagging through natural language processes,
这650万条消息，通过自然语言系统自动标注

130
00:07:10.180 --> 00:07:11.676
all of these data points --
根据所有的数据点

131
00:07:11.700 --> 00:07:16.580
I can tell you that the worst day of the week for eating disorders: Monday.
我得说一周中饮食失调最严重的一天是周一

132
00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:21.740
The worst time of day for substance abuse: 5am.
一天中滥用药物最严重的时间是上午五点

133
00:07:22.700 --> 00:07:25.156
And that Montana is a beautiful place to visit
美丽的蒙大纳州是一个值得参观的地方

134
00:07:25.180 --> 00:07:26.956
but you do not want to live there,
但你不会想在那儿生活

135
00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:30.540
because it is the number one state for suicidal ideation.
因为那是在我们数据库里自杀意念排第一位的州

136
00:07:31.740 --> 00:07:35.636
And we've made this data public and free and open.
我们已经公开免费公布了这一数据

137
00:07:35.660 --> 00:07:38.756
We've pulled all the personally identifiable information.
我们已经获得了所有个人的、可确认的信息

138
00:07:38.780 --> 00:07:42.036
And it's in a place called CrisisTrends.org.
这些信息被公布在危机趋势这个网站上

139
00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:47.396
Because I want schools to be able to see
因为我希望学校能注意到

140
00:07:47.420 --> 00:07:49.756
that Monday is the worst day for eating disorders,
周一是饮食失调最严重的一天

141
00:07:49.780 --> 00:07:51.636
so that they can plan meals
因此学校工作人员可以调整食物计划

142
00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:54.076
and guidance counselors to be there on Mondays.
并且周一也会有引导咨询师在场协助

143
00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:58.836
And I want families to see that substance abuse questions spike at 5am.
我也希望所有家庭能够知道滥用药物的高峰期是早上五点

144
00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:03.140
I want somebody to take care of those Native American reservations in Montana.
我希望有人能够关心在蒙大纳州的美国本地人保留区

145
00:08:03.780 --> 00:08:05.836
(Applause)
（鼓掌）

146
00:08:05.860 --> 00:08:08.140
Data, evidence
数据，证据

147
00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:10.876
makes policy, research,
促使政策，研究

148
00:08:10.900 --> 00:08:15.076
journalism, policing, school boards -- everything better.
报章杂志，行政监管和教育委员会，所有的事都变得更好

149
00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:18.476
I don't think of myself as a mental health activist.
我不觉得自己是一个关注精神健康的活跃分子

150
00:08:18.500 --> 00:08:22.636
I think of myself as a national health activist.
但我觉得自己是一个关注国民健康的活跃分子

151
00:08:22.660 --> 00:08:25.540
I get really excited about this data, I'm a little nerdy.
